    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-03-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-03-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="228"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d228">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.002/3–2249: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-03-22">March 22,
                            1949</date>.<lb/>[Received March 22—7:28 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>615. Acting President announced personnel new Cabinet March 21. <hi rend="italic"
                        >Chung Tang Jih Pao</hi> lists membership as follows: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Vice-Premier: Chia Ching-te.</p>
                        <p>Ministers without Portfolio: Chang Chih-chung, Chang Chun, Chu Chia-hua,
                            Mo Te-hui, Ho Yao-tsu.</p>
                        <p>Secretary-General: Huang Chao-ku.</p>
                        <p>Deputy Secretary-General: Ni Chiung-sheng</p>
                        <p>Minister of Interior: Li Han-hun.</p>
                        <p>Foreign Affairs: Fu Ping-chang.<note n="38" xml:id="d228fn38">Foo
                                Ping-sheung, Chinese Ambassador in the Soviet Union.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Economy: Sun Yueh-chi.</p>
                        <p>Finance: Liu Kung-yun.<note n="39" xml:id="d228fn39">Known also as S. Y.
                                Liu.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Education: Han Li-wu.</p>
                        <p>National Defense: Hsu Yung-chang.</p>
                        <p>Communications: Tuan Mu-chieh.<note n="40" xml:id="d228fn40">Known also
                                as Tuan Mu-kai (or Joseph K. Twammoh).</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Justice: Chang Chih-pen.</p>
                        <p>Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission: Pai Yun-ti.</p>
                        <p>Overseas Chinese Affairs Commission: Tai Kuei-shang.</p>
                        <p>Bureau of Audit: Pang Sung-chou.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Acting President simultaneously promulgated revised organic law of Executive
                    Yuan, reducing number of Ministries to those listed above, in accordance with
                    measure previously passed by Legislative Yuan.</p>
                <p>Repeated AmEmb Canton and Shanghai unnumbered.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
